title: Ability to query by max characters instead of top-k
body:
I could see it being useful in cases where you have a mix of small/large chunks of text. If you set `top-k=3`, it may not return enough text to provide proper context. In such cases, you can request to receive as many chunks as possible, provided that their total character count is less than n. In most cases, I would prefer to use character size rather than top-k.

something like `res = collection.vector_search(“What is pgml”, max_char=600)`

Especially in cases where you are chunking you may want to stuff as much text into context as possible, which is hard with top-k. I guess you could set a high top-k and then truncate the results to match the character size you want.

v4.30.0: 100k, Agents improvements, Safetensors core dependency, Swiftformer, Autoformer, MobileViTv2, timm-as-a-backbone

100k

Transformers has just reached 100k stars on GitHub, and to celebrate we wanted to highlight 100 projects in the vicinity of transformers and we have decided to create an awesome-transformers page to do just that.

We accept PRs to add projects to the list!

  • Top 100 by @​LysandreJik in #22912

4-bit quantization and QLoRA

By leveraging the bitsandbytes library by @​TimDettmers, we add 4-bit support to transformers models!

  • 4-bit QLoRA via bitsandbytes (4-bit base model + LoRA) by @​TimDettmers in #23479

Agents

The Agents framework has been improved and continues to be stabilized. Among bug fixes, here are the important new features that were added:

  • Local agent capabilities, to load a generative model directly from transformers instead of relying on APIs.
  • Prompts are now hosted on the Hub, which means that anyone can fork the prompts and update them with theirs, to let other community contributors re-use them

Safetensors

The safetensors library is a safe serialization framework for machine learning tensors. It has been audited and will become the default serialization framework for several organizations (Hugging Face, EleutherAI, Stability AI).

It has now become a core dependency of transformers.

  • Making safetensors a core dependency. by @​Narsil in #23254

New models

Swiftformer

The SwiftFormer paper introduces a novel efficient additive attention mechanism that effectively replaces the quadratic matrix multiplication operations in the self-attention computation with linear element-wise multiplications. A series of models called ‘SwiftFormer’ is built based on this, which achieves state-of-the-art performance in terms of both accuracy and mobile inference speed. Even their small variant achieves 78.5% top-1 ImageNet1K accuracy with only 0.8 ms latency on iPhone 14, which is more accurate and 2× faster compared to MobileViT-v2.

  • Add swiftformer by @​shehanmunasinghe in #22686

Autoformer

This model augments the Transformer as a deep decomposition architecture, which can progressively decompose the trend and seasonal components during the forecasting process.

title: Incorrect operator used in pgvector example for the query to use the index
body:
In the pgvector example mentioned in [embedding](https://postgresml.org/docs/guides/transformers/embeddings) section of the documentation, a wrong operator is used for the query to take advantage of the index. The `<->` operator is used for L2 distance while `<=>` is the corect operator for cosine distance. The created index uses `pgvector.vector_cosine_ops` operator class. So the correct operator to use should be `<=>`.
Similiarly, for the query to use the index, one could change the operator class to `pgvector.vector_l2_op`.

For more information regarding pgvector, see the following sections of the pgvector README.md:
[Indexing](https://github.com/pgvector/pgvector/tree/master#indexing)
[Vector Operators](https://github.com/pgvector/pgvector/blob/master/README.md#vector-operators)

title: Create query builder interface for pgml.collection
body:
I think our API needs to consist of composable functions to generate sql fragements, rather than adding a bunch of duplicate-ish functions that support some subsets.

I imagine a pgml.query module with a Query class that has an interface like like:

- `def vector_recall(self, str) -> self`
- `def text_recall(self, str) -> self`
- `def trigram_recall(self, str) -> self`
- `def limit(self, int) -> self`
- `def order(self, str) -> self`
- `def filter(self, dict) -> self`
- `def select(self, fields: list[str] or dict) -> self` # fetch vectors or metadata subfields or document text
- `def explain(self, analyze: bool) -> self` # make it an explain plan
- `def to_sql(self) -> str`

So I can write code like:

``` 
collection.query().vector_recall('hi mom').limit(10).fetch() -> list[Document]
```
or 
``` 
collection.query().text_recall('hi mom').limit(10).fetch() -> list[Document]
```
or 
``` 
collection.query().vector_recall('hi mom').text_recall('hi mom').filter({"name": "bob"}).limit(10).fetch() -> list[Document]
```

Each intermediate result after `collection.query()` is a `Query`, and we can start building other query functions that take queries as  arguments to generate CTE's or subqueries for more advanced use cases. With a query object like this, we can also develop more complex (AND/OR/NOT) predicates as well for filters.

We should take a survey of existing query builders ORMs and APIs to make sure we're not backing ourselves into an immediate corner, but ultimately we want this to be a multi language SDK, so we'll be implementing it from SQL primitives, and it should closely mirror that structure.

 - [pypika](https://pypika.readthedocs.io/en/latest/_modules/pypika/queries.html#CreateQueryBuilder)
 - [active_record](https://guides.rubyonrails.org/active_record_querying.html)
 - [elastic](https://elastic-builder.js.org/docs/)

title: Adding embed_array for getting the embeddings of multiple strings
body:
Works the same way as pgml.embed but can take an array of inputs. Example:

```sql

    inputs => ARRAY['Hello', 'World'],

);

```sql

    transformer => 'hkunlp/instructor-base', 
    inputs => ARRAY['Hello World', 'I love Rust'],
    kwargs => '{"device": "cpu", "instruction": "Represent the content for retrieving supporting documents:"}'::JSONB
);

body: We have anecdotal evidence that the Python layer in between libtorch and Postgres calls can increase the cost as much as 4x when doing large batches. title: Embedding vector search is performed on RAM?
body:
Most vector database algorithms are carried out in RAM. Where are the PostgreSQL database embeddings stored? Should we expect them stored on disk like how ordinary postgresql databases file stored? Which means no large RAM is required for large embedding vectors dataset.

Almost all other vector databases are RAM and not disk based, so this will be nice if postgres stands out by operating like any sql database without huge RAM requirements.

How about pgvector?

Release notes

Sourced from requests's releases.

v2.31.0

2.31.0 (2023-05-22)

Security

  • Versions of Requests between v2.3.0 and v2.30.0 are vulnerable to potential forwarding of Proxy-Authorization headers to destination servers when following HTTPS redirects.

    When proxies are defined with user info (https://user:pass@proxy:8080), Requests will construct a Proxy-Authorization header that is attached to the request to authenticate with the proxy.

    In cases where Requests receives a redirect response, it previously reattached the Proxy-Authorization header incorrectly, resulting in the value being sent through the tunneled connection to the destination server. Users who rely on defining their proxy credentials in the URL are strongly encouraged to upgrade to Requests 2.31.0+ to prevent unintentional leakage and rotate their proxy credentials once the change has been fully deployed.

    Users who do not use a proxy or do not supply their proxy credentials through the user information portion of their proxy URL are not subject to this vulnerability.

    Full details can be read in our Github Security Advisory and CVE-2023-32681.
